SIMPLE: pew
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pew
<hw>Pew</hw> <pr>(p⟦umac⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>pewe</ets>, OF. <ets>puie</ets> parapet, balustrade, balcony, fr.
L. <ets>podium</ets> an elevated place, a jutty, balcony, a parapet or
balcony in the circus, where the emperor and other distinguished persons
sat, Gr. <grk>po`dion</grk>, dim. of <grk>poy`s</grk>,
<grk>podo`s</grk>, foot; -- hence the Latin sense of a raised place
(orig. as a rest or support for the foot). See <er>Foot</er>, and cf.
<er>Podium</er>, <er>Poy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One of the
compartments in a church which are separated by low partitions, and have
long seats upon which several persons may sit; -- sometimes called
<altname>slip</altname>. Pews were originally made square, but are now
usually long and narrow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any structure shaped like a church pew, as a stall,
formerly used by money lenders, etc.; a box in theater; a pen; a
sheepfold.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Pepys.</au>
<au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pew opener</b></col>, <cd>an usher in a church.</cd>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Dickens.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pew</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pew
<hw>Pew</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To furnish with pews.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Ash.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pewee</ent>⟦br⟧
